A6. Stages 6–8: Topic Formation (Hierarchy Tree)

Parameter = Value	Why This Value
max_depth = 5 hops	UMLS has 8–12 levels on average. 5 hops reaches the mid-level of most branches (specific enough to be clinically meaningful). Going deeper hits root-adjacent concepts like 'Disease' (IC~1) that would group everything. The IC gradient check (below) provides the real adaptive stopping.
_HTB_IC_GRADIENT_RATIO = 0.3	At hop 3+, a parent is only followed if its IC ≥ 30% of the current node’s IC. This catches the 'IC cliff' where concepts suddenly become very broad. Example: 'Persistent asthma' (IC=10.8) → parent 'Asthma' (IC=7.4). Ratio = 7.4/10.8 = 0.69 > 0.3 → follow. But 'Asthma' → 'Disease' (IC=1.2): 1.2/7.4 = 0.16 < 0.3 → stop. The 2-hop grace period ensures direct parents are always included regardless of IC.
_HTB_IC_FLOOR_PERCENTILE = 10	p10 of surviving CUI ICs. For a specific store (knee surgery CUIs, ICs 12–15): floor ≈ 12.5 — only very specific ancestors qualify. For a general store (ICs 3–15): floor ≈ 4.5 — allows broader groupers. p10 (not mean or median) ensures the floor is driven by the least specific concepts, not the bulk. This prevents outlier low-IC CUIs from dragging the floor down.
max_coverage = max(2, n/√n)	From IDF literature: document frequency √n is the threshold for 'too common'. An ancestor covering more than n/√n CUIs is so broad it provides no discrimination. Small store (n=5): max=2 (tight). Large store (n=100): max=10 (relaxed). Always ≥2 because a convergence point must cover at least 2 CUIs by definition.
Convergence rule: ≥2 CUIs, not in surviving set	≥2 ensures the ancestor actually groups concepts (singletons can’t converge). 'Not in surviving set' prevents a surviving CUI from being its own grouping key, which would create degenerate topics of size 1.
Subtopic: highest IC first, greedy	Most specific convergence points get first pick of unassigned CUIs. This ensures subtopics are as specific as possible. Greedy assignment prevents a CUI from appearing in multiple subtopics (each CUI belongs to exactly one).
Topic grouper: ancestor of 2+ subtopics	The grouper is one level above the subtopics. If it only covered 1 subtopic, the topic would be redundant (same as the subtopic). 2+ ensures the topic adds a level of organization.
_REP_HAC_THRESHOLD = 0.5 (Stage 7)	HAC (average linkage) cut distance for sub-clustering within a topic. 0.5 cosine distance = 0.5 cosine similarity. Members above 0.5 similarity are in the same sub-cluster and share a representative. Below: different sub-clusters, different reps. Empirically tested: 0.3 over-splits (too many reps), 0.7 under-splits (one rep per topic).
_ANCHOR_IC_MIN = 4.0 (Stage 7)	IC=4.0 in UMLS corresponds to concepts covering ~2% of the hierarchy (e^{-4} ≈ 0.018). Below IC=4: concepts are so broad they route to too many topics ('Clinical finding', 'Body structure'). Above IC=4: specific enough to be useful routing anchors.
_ANCHOR_BFS_DEPTH = 4 (Stage 7)	Anchors are routing shortcuts for storage. 4 hops UP from a representative finds mid-level ancestors suitable for indexing. Fewer hops: anchors too specific (many duplicates). More hops: anchors too broad (poor discrimination).

Stage 6 (HierarchicalTopicBuilder): Takes the 5 surviving CUIs (just CUI codes — no phrases, no text). BFS walks UP the UMLS hierarchy per CUI, collecting ancestors. Convergence points (ancestors covering 2+ CUIs) become grouping keys.

IC floor = p10 of surviving CUI ICs ≈ 14.8. Only very specific ancestors are eligible.
Max coverage = max(2, 5/√5) = 2. A convergence point can cover at most 2 CUIs in a store this small.

