Part B (Appendix): The Full Louvain Path

Why this section exists: In Case 1, every entity had ≤20 CUIs after hierarchy reduction, so Louvain was always skipped. But if a clinical note contains a detailed surgical description or complex medication regimen, a single entity can produce >20 SNOMED CUIs. This section walks through what happens in that case.

Hypothetical entity: "complex cardiac catheterization with multi-vessel stenting, balloon angioplasty, intravascular imaging, and hemodynamic monitoring" — producing 28 SNOMED CUIs after Stages 2–4.

B6.1 Overview: What Changes When n > 20

The pipeline path is:

n ≤ 20 (Case 1, all entities): Otsu + guards only ("fast path"). Dedup first, then pass survivors as a flat group to Stage 6 (HierarchicalTopicBuilder).

n > 20 (this example, 28 CUIs): Otsu + guards FIRST to remove true duplicates. Then, if survivors still > 20, Louvain builds a cosine k-NN graph and detects semantic communities. These communities become the initial topic structure, which Stage 6 then refines.

The full Stage 5 pipeline for n > 20:
Step	What It Does	Code Location
1. Otsu + guards	Remove true duplicates (same as n ≤ 20)	_reduce_topic()
2. k-NN graph	Find 20 nearest neighbors per CUI by cosine similarity	_cosine_knn()
3. Adaptive edge threshold	Mean of k-th neighbor distances → edge cutoff	TopicBuilder.build()
4. Weighted graph	Edges where cosine distance < threshold. Weight = similarity.	TopicBuilder.build()
5. Louvain detection	Community detection on weighted graph (resolution=1.0, seed=42)	networkx louvain_communities()
6. Silhouette splitting	Data-driven quality check. Split poor communities at resolution=2.0.	_split_communities_by_silhouette()
7. Singleton merging	Merge isolated CUIs into nearest group if similarity > threshold	TopicBuilder.build()
8. Within-community dedup	Otsu + 4 structural guards within each community	_reduce_topic() per community

B6.2 Step 1: Initial Dedup (Otsu + Guards)

Input: 28 SNOMED CUIs from the cardiac catheterization entity, each with a 3072-dim L2-normalized embedding.

Same process as the query side (Section A5): cosine distance matrix (28×28 = 378 pairwise distances) → Otsu threshold → HAC clustering at tight_t → within-cluster guard checks.

Result: 28 → 24 CUIs. 4 true duplicates removed (e.g., 'PTCA of LAD' and 'Percutaneous transluminal coronary angioplasty of left anterior descending artery' — same procedure, different SNOMED codes, all 4 guards failed).

24 > 20 → Louvain runs on the 24 survivors.

B6.3 Steps 2–3: Cosine k-NN Graph Construction

What: For each of the 24 CUIs, find the k=20 most similar CUIs by cosine similarity.

How _cosine_knn works:
  1. Build 24×24 similarity matrix: matrix @ matrix.T (dot product of L2-normalized vectors = cosine similarity)
  2. Set diagonal to −∞ (a CUI is not its own neighbor)
  3. For each row, argpartition to find top-20 indices
  4. Sort those 20 by similarity (highest first)
  5. Return: neighbors[24×20] (indices), sim_scores[24×20] (similarities)

Note: k=min(20, n−1) = min(20, 23) = 20. Each CUI has exactly 20 neighbors listed. But not all become edges — the adaptive threshold filters weak connections.

Adaptive edge threshold: For each CUI, the k-th (20th) neighbor's distance is recorded. This is the weakest connection in that CUI's neighborhood. The threshold = mean of all these k-th distances across all 24 CUIs.

Concrete example:
CUI	20th neighbor distance	Meaning
PTCA of LAD	0.28	Its 20th neighbor is fairly close (dense neighborhood)
Hemodynamic monitoring	0.45	Its 20th neighbor is far (sparse neighborhood)
Balloon angioplasty	0.31	Moderate density
...(21 more)	0.25–0.50	Varies by concept

threshold = mean(all k-th distances) ≈ 0.35
Only pairs with cosine distance < 0.35 (i.e., similarity > 0.65) get an edge in the graph.

B6.4 Step 4: Building the Weighted Graph

What: A networkx Graph with 24 nodes (one per CUI). An edge is added between CUI-i and CUI-j if their cosine distance < threshold (0.35). Edge weight = cosine similarity.

Result: ~85 edges out of 276 possible (24×23/2). The graph is sparse — only genuinely related concepts are connected.

What the graph looks like (conceptually):
Cluster	CUIs Connected	Internal Edges
Stenting procedures	Coronary stent placement, DES insertion, multi-vessel stenting, stent delivery	Dense connections (sim > 0.75)
Angioplasty procedures	Balloon angioplasty, PTCA, dilation catheter, guidewire	Dense connections (sim > 0.70)
Imaging	Intravascular ultrasound, OCT, angiography, contrast injection	Moderate connections (sim > 0.65)
Monitoring	Hemodynamic monitoring, pressure measurement, ECG	Moderate connections (sim > 0.65)
Cross-cluster	Stenting ↔ Angioplasty (related but distinct procedures)	Few weak edges (sim ≈ 0.66)

The graph naturally separates into clusters. Louvain's job is to find these clusters automatically.

B6.5 Step 5: Louvain Community Detection

What Louvain does: Finds groups of nodes that are more densely connected to each other than to the rest of the graph. Maximizes "modularity" — a score measuring how much the grouping improves over random.

Algorithm (simplified):
  Phase 1: Each node starts in its own community. For each node, try moving it to each neighbor's community. If modularity increases, make the move. Repeat until no moves improve modularity.
  Phase 2: Collapse each community into a single super-node. Build a new graph of super-nodes. Repeat Phase 1 on this smaller graph.
  Repeat Phases 1–2 until no further improvement.

Parameters:
Parameter	Value	Why
resolution	1.0	Standard resolution. Higher = more communities (finer split). Used at 2.0 only during silhouette re-splitting.
seed	42	Deterministic. Same input → same communities every time.
weight	"weight"	Uses the cosine similarity edge weights. Stronger connections count more.

Result for our 24 CUIs:
Community	Size	CUIs	Clinical Meaning
0	7	Coronary stent, DES, multi-vessel stent, stent delivery, ...	Stenting procedures
1	6	Balloon angioplasty, PTCA, dilation catheter, guidewire, ...	Angioplasty procedures
2	5	IVUS, OCT, angiography, contrast, fluoroscopy	Imaging modalities
3	4	Hemodynamic monitoring, pressure, ECG, arterial line	Monitoring
4	2	Vascular access, sheath insertion	Access procedures

5 communities detected. Louvain grouped semantically related CUIs together — stenting with stenting, imaging with imaging. The cross-cluster edges (stenting ↔ angioplasty) were too weak to merge them.

B6.6 Step 6: Silhouette-Based Quality Check

Why: Louvain doesn't guarantee that every community is well-formed. A community might contain two sub-groups that should be separate. Silhouette scoring measures how well each community holds together.

Silhouette score per community: For each CUI in a community, compute:
  a_i = mean distance to other CUIs in the SAME community (cohesion)
  b_i = mean distance to CUIs in the NEAREST OTHER community (separation)
  s_i = (b_i − a_i) / max(a_i, b_i)
  Community score = mean of s_i across all members

Interpretation:
Score Range	Meaning
+1.0	Perfect: CUIs are much closer to own community than to any other
+0.5 to +1.0	Good: clear community structure
0.0 to +0.5	Weak: community may contain sub-groups
Below 0.0	Poor: CUIs are closer to another community than their own

Scores for our 5 communities:
Community	Silhouette Score	Assessment
0 (Stenting)	0.72	Good — stenting CUIs are well-grouped
1 (Angioplasty)	0.68	Good
2 (Imaging)	0.45	Weak — IVUS and angiography may be sub-groups
3 (Monitoring)	0.71	Good
4 (Access)	0.80	Good (only 2 members, naturally tight)

Gap detection: Sort scores: [0.80, 0.72, 0.71, 0.68, 0.45]. Gaps: [0.08, 0.01, 0.03, 0.23]. Largest gap = 0.23 (between 0.68 and 0.45). Is 0.23 > 2.0 × median gap (0.055)? Yes → Community 2 flagged for splitting.

Re-split: Community 2 (Imaging, 5 members) is re-processed with Louvain at resolution=2.0 (forces finer communities). Result:
  Sub-community 2a: {IVUS, OCT} (invasive imaging)
  Sub-community 2b: {angiography, contrast, fluoroscopy} (radiographic imaging)

New silhouette scores for 2a and 2b are both above the threshold → accepted.

Final communities: 6 (was 5). The Imaging community was split into invasive vs radiographic imaging. All other communities unchanged.

B6.7 Step 7: Singleton Merging

What: If Louvain or silhouette splitting produced isolated CUIs (communities of size 1), each singleton is compared against all group centroids.

Merge threshold (data-driven):
  1. Compute pairwise cosine similarities within every group
  2. merge_min_sim = mean(within-group similarities) × 0.5
  3. Clamped to [0.1, 0.9]

Meaning: a singleton must be at least 50% as similar to a group as the group's own members are to each other. If within-group similarity averages 0.80, the singleton needs at least 0.40 cosine similarity to join.

In our example: No singletons produced. All 24 CUIs belong to communities of size ≥2.

B6.8 Step 8: Within-Community Dedup

What: After Louvain has formed communities, Otsu + 4 structural guards run WITHIN each community. This is the same _reduce_topic logic used in the fast path, but scoped to the community's CUIs only.

Why run dedup after Louvain? Louvain groups related CUIs together. But 'related' doesn't mean 'different'. Within the Stenting community, 'coronary stent placement' and 'coronary stent deployment' may be the same procedure with different SNOMED codes. The structural guards catch these.

Example — Community 0 (Stenting, 7 CUIs):
Pair Checked	Distance	Guard Result	Action
Coronary stent placement vs Coronary stent deployment	0.03	All 4 guards fail (same type, same ancestors, not parent-child, not sibling leaves)	REMOVE deployment (lower centroid sim)
DES insertion vs Bare metal stent	0.09	Guard 2 fires: different subtypes of stent (disjoint sub-categories)	KEEP BOTH
Multi-vessel stent vs Single-vessel stent	0.11	Guard 4 fires: sibling leaf nodes under same parent	KEEP BOTH

Result: Community 0: 7 → 6 CUIs (1 true duplicate removed).
Across all 6 communities: 24 → 21 CUIs total. 3 within-community duplicates removed.

B6.9 Complete Stage 5 Flow (n > 20)

Step	Input	Output	What Happened
Stages 1–4	Raw CUIs from API	28 SNOMED CUIs	SAB filter + hierarchy reduction
Otsu + guards	28 CUIs	24 CUIs	4 true duplicates removed
k-NN graph	24 CUIs	24 nodes, ~85 edges	k=20, threshold=0.35
Louvain	Graph with 85 edges	5 communities	Modularity-based grouping
Silhouette	5 communities	6 communities	1 weak community re-split
Singleton merge	6 communities, 0 singletons	6 communities	Nothing to merge
Within-community dedup	24 CUIs in 6 communities	21 CUIs in 6 communities	3 intra-community duplicates

28 → 21 CUIs. 7 total removed: 4 by initial Otsu, 3 by within-community Otsu. Louvain itself does not remove CUIs — it only groups them. The dedup happens before and after Louvain via the same Otsu + guard logic.

Key point for demo: Louvain organizes. Guards protect. Otsu finds the threshold. No CUI is removed without passing through 4 structural checks. The hierarchy, semantic types, and ancestor sets all have to agree that two CUIs are truly the same concept before one is dropped.
 
QUERY MATCHING PIPELINE (ADAPTIVE SCORER)
Topic Gate → 3-Signal Scoring → Z-Score → Relative Threshold → Results

Part C: Query Matching

Query: "knee arthroplasty" (1 topic, 5 CUIs, 1 centroid)
Store: 5 documents (including Case 1), 236 topic groups total

Scoring parameters (all in topic_matcher.py DEFAULTS):
Parameter = Value	Why This Value
z_score_normalize = True	Z-score auto-weights each signal by its standard deviation (discriminative power) for THIS query. A broad query where vec_sim has high variance and cui_ratio has zero variance: z-score gives all weight to vec_sim automatically. Manual weights (0.40/0.30/0.30) can’t adapt per query.
w_cui/w_vec/w_lin = 0.40/0.30/0.30	Fallback only (z_score=False). 0.40 for CUI overlap reflects that exact concept matches are the strongest evidence. 0.30/0.30 for vec_sim and Lin are equal because neither is systematically stronger. Empirically stable across test stores.
anc_depth = 8	Search-time BFS is deeper than ingestion-time (3–5) because at query time we want to find ALL hierarchy relationships, not just direct parents. 8 hops reaches mid-UMLS (IC ≈ 3–4). Deeper adds no matches because IC pruning stops it. Shallower misses valid cousin relationships.
score_ratio = 0.40	Return results scoring ≥ 40% of the top score. 0.40 = broad recall — keeps the relevant cluster and drops the noise tail. Tested: 0.30 returns too much noise, 0.60 misses secondary matches. 0.40 is the point where precision stops improving and recall starts dropping.
score_min = 0.01	Structural floor, not a tuning parameter. Catches floating-point artifacts (scores of 0.001 from z-score normalization when all candidates are nearly identical). Any real match scores well above 0.01.
Zero-evidence guard: all 3 = 0.0	The only safe suppression: literally zero evidence on all three channels. Any non-zero value (even vec_sim=0.05) means SOME signal exists and the combined score should decide. Per-signal thresholds were removed because they suppress the channel that carries evidence for broad queries.
group_dist = 0.15	Cosine distance for cross-chunk topic grouping in TopicIndex.build(). 0.15 = 0.85 cosine similarity. Topics from different clinical notes must be very similar to be grouped together. Tested: 0.10 under-groups (too many groups), 0.25 over-groups (merges distinct conditions).
variant_min_change = 1	Minimum CUI adds+removes to flag a variant between consecutive notes in the same topic group. 1 = any change is flagged. Set to 2+ only if you want to ignore trivial edits.

Adaptive parameters (derived at runtime from store data):
Parameter = Value	Why This Formula
filter_min_ancestor_ic = 13.98	p25 of store CUI ICs. Ancestors below this IC are too broad to be meaningful shared ancestors. p25 (not median) because we want the floor driven by the lower quartile — most ancestors should be above this. Specific store (ICs 12–15) → high floor (13.98). General store (ICs 3–15) → low floor (≈4).
ic_weight_alpha = 0.90	query_ic_mean / max_store_ic. Specific query against specific store → alpha near 1.0 → IC dominates over IDF in cui_ratio weighting. Broad query ('worsening condition', low IC CUIs) → alpha near 0.1 → IDF dominates. Adapts automatically to query specificity.
ic_prune_ratio = 0.711	p10/p50 of store ICs. Controls BFS ancestor pruning depth at search time. Specific store: p10 and p50 are close (ratio → 0.7+) → tight pruning (stop early). General store: ratio → 0.2 → relaxed pruning (search deeper). Clamped [0.1, 0.9].
sibling_ic_ratio = 0.944	p25/p75 of store ICs. MICA IC gate for sibling matching. Specific store (narrow IC range): ratio near 1.0 → only very close siblings accepted. General store: ratio → 0.3 → distant siblings OK. Prevents false sibling matches in specific stores.
min_best_lin = 0.278	2×root_ic / (query_ic_mean + store_ic_mean) × 1.5. Lin similarity of two unrelated concepts sharing only the root ancestor. Below this = the pair is no more related than random CUIs. ChunkMatcher hard-negative blocker only.
use_idf = True	Shannon entropy of the store’s IDF distribution > 0.3. High entropy = IDF values are spread out = IDF is discriminative for this store. Low entropy = most CUIs have similar IDF = IDF adds noise. Computed once per store.

